Production objects carry only their schema fields. Page numbers, evidence,
confidence, reasons, and warnings go in audit — never inside a production record.

audit.notes is free text. Use it for source decisions, name and institution variants,
grouped affiliations, retained combined expressions, fallbacks, exclusions, float
enrichment, rejoined emails, apparent misspellings, formatting problems, and anything
found outside a table.

audit.coverage.pages_reviewed is a count, not a list.


9. Order of construction


Review every page.
Identify each person-bearing table's type by its subject (§3.2).
Extract PI candidates from the program table; extract leadership only from the roster.
Resolve field values against anchors (§3.5).
Split every combined responsibility into atomic records, verbatim (§3.4).
Deduplicate.
Build float records; propagate shared narrative details.
Extract instruments from tables, then narrative; preserve distinct units.
Exclude software, shore-only, and historical equipment.
Merge repeated serials.
Finalize the arrays.
Count the finalized arrays. counts must equal actual array lengths — recount and
correct before returning.
Return JSON.



10. Before returning


Every page reviewed; coverage accurate.
Every scientific PI record traces to the program table; the only roster records are
leadership.
No PI record holds two independent responsibilities.
Atomic values are verbatim; no qualifier was distributed across split items.
No grouped multi-person affiliation was assigned to an individual where a specific
source exists.
Names and institutions are as the anchor wrote them; no cross-record normalization.
Floats are floats; no ID was assumed to be a WMO number; shared details propagated.
Every serial resolves to exactly one record; distinct units not collapsed.
Software, shore-only, and historical equipment excluded and noted.
All schema fields present, ordered, whitespace-stripped; missing scalars null.
counts equal actual array lengths.
Valid JSON. Starts
